#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:1
msgid "Kernels and Device Functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:3
msgid ""
"A **kernel** is a function that runs on the GPU -- the entry point that the "
"host launches across thousands of threads. A **device function** is a helper "
"that runs on the GPU but can only be called from another device function or "
"kernel, never from the host. This chapter covers both, along with the Rust "
"patterns that are (and aren't) supported in device code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:10
msgid ""
"[CUDA Programming Guide -- Kernels](https://docs.nvidia.com/cuda/cuda-"
"programming-guide/#kernels) for the authoritative CUDA C++ reference on "
"kernel and device functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:14
msgid "`#[kernel]` -- the GPU entry point"
msgstr "`#[kernel]` -- GPU 進入點"

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:16
msgid ""
"Annotating a function with `#[kernel]` tells cuda-oxide to compile it as a "
"GPU entry point. The function must return `()` -- kernels communicate "
"results by writing to output buffers, not by returning values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:20
msgid ""
"use cuda_device::{kernel, thread, DisjointSlice};\n"
"\n"
"#[kernel]\n"
"pub fn vecadd(a: &[f32], b: &[f32], mut c: DisjointSlice<f32>) {\n"
"    let idx = thread::index_1d();\n"
"    if let Some(c_elem) = c.get_mut(idx) {\n"
"        *c_elem = a[idx.get()] + b[idx.get()];\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:32
msgid "Under the hood, `#[kernel]` does three things:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:34
msgid ""
"**Renames** the function into the reserved `cuda_oxide_kernel_<hash>_<name>` "
"namespace so the compiler's collector can identify it as a device entry "
"point. The exact prefix is owned by the workspace-internal `reserved-oxide-"
"symbols` crate; the `<hash>` suffix makes the namespace unguessable for user "
"code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:39
msgid ""
"**Adds `#[no_mangle]`** to preserve the symbol name in the generated PTX."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:40
msgid ""
"**Generates host lookup metadata** so typed launch code can find the correct "
"PTX entry. Generic kernels also get a readable helper such as "
"`scale_ptx_name::<f32>()`; generated marker types are internal plumbing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:44
msgid ""
"In the generated PTX, a kernel becomes a `.entry` directive -- the GPU "
"equivalent of `main`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:47
msgid ".entry vecadd(.param .u64 a, .param .u64 a_len, ...) { ... }\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:51
msgid "Parameter constraints"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:53
msgid ""
"Kernel parameters cross the host/device ABI boundary through **argument "
"scalarization** (covered in the [Memory and Data Movement](memory-and-data-"
"movement.md) chapter). The key rules:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:58
msgid "**Slices** (`&[T]`, `DisjointSlice<T>`) become a pointer + length pair."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:59
msgid "**Scalars** (`u32`, `f32`, etc.) are passed directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:60
msgid ""
"**Structs and closures by value** travel as a single byval `.param`. The "
"field-by-field flattening still applies to internal device-to-device calls, "
"but the kernel boundary itself receives the whole aggregate as one value to "
"match the single packet slot the host launcher pushes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:64
msgid ""
"**No heap-allocated types** (`Vec`, `String`, `Box`) -- the `alloc` crate is "
"allowed through the compiler, but no device-side `#[global_allocator]` is "
"configured today. Even with one, device `malloc` is extremely slow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:68
msgid "Device helper functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:70
msgid ""
"Not all GPU code belongs in the kernel itself. You can factor logic into "
"helper functions that the compiler will also compile for the GPU."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:73
msgid "Auto-discovered helpers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:75
msgid ""
"The simplest approach: just write a normal Rust function and call it from "
"your kernel. The compiler's **collector** traverses the call graph from each "
"`#[kernel]` entry point and automatically compiles every reachable function "
"for the GPU -- no annotation needed:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:80
msgid ""
"fn clamp(x: f32, lo: f32, hi: f32) -> f32 {\n"
"    if x < lo { lo } else if x > hi { hi } else { x }\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"#[kernel]\n"
"pub fn apply_clamp(input: &[f32], mut out: DisjointSlice<f32>) {\n"
"    let idx = thread::index_1d();\n"
"    if let Some(out_elem) = out.get_mut(idx) {\n"
"        *out_elem = clamp(input[idx.get()], 0.0, 1.0);\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:94
msgid ""
"The `clamp` function is compiled to a PTX `.func` (device function) and "
"typically inlined by the compiler, so there is no call overhead."
msgstr ""

