"directives."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:305
msgid "`no_std` and panic behavior"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:307
msgid ""
"Device code runs in an implicit `#![no_std]` environment. You do not need to "
"add this attribute yourself -- the compiler backend handles it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:310
msgid ""
"**Panic behavior:** all unwind paths in MIR are treated as unreachable. If a "
"panic actually triggers at runtime (e.g., an array bounds check fails), the "
"GPU executes a **trap instruction**, which causes the host to receive "
"`CUDA_ERROR_ILLEGAL_INSTRUCTION`. This is semantically equivalent to "
"`panic=abort` but does not require any special compiler flags."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:316
msgid "In practice this means:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:318
msgid "`unwrap()` and `expect()` work but will trap the GPU on `None`/`Err`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:319
msgid "`assert!` and `debug_assert!` work but trap on failure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:320
msgid ""
"`panic!(\"message\")` is **not** supported (the formatting machinery is "
"unavailable) -- use `gpu_assert!` or `debug::trap()` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/kernels-and-device-functions.md:324
msgid ""
"The [Error Handling and Debugging](error-handling-and-debugging.md) chapter "
"covers `gpu_printf!`, `gpu_assert!`, and `cargo oxide debug` for diagnosing "
"kernel failures."
msgstr ""
